    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Thinking E-2 is Automatic</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Grenada citizenship makes you ELIGIBLE for E-2—it doesn't guarantee approval. E-2 requires separate application with substantial US business investment, viable business plan, and proper documentation. Budget $100K-200K+ for US investment and $15K-25K for E-2 legal fees.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating E-2 Investment Amount</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">"Substantial" investment for E-2 varies but typically $100K-200K minimum for service businesses, more for capital-intensive operations. Investing $50K rarely qualifies. Consult E-2 immigration attorney before committing to ensure your business plan meets requirements.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Expecting E-2 to Lead to Green Card</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">E-2 is NOT a path to Green Card or US citizenship directly. You can renew indefinitely, but it doesn't convert to permanent residence. If you ultimately want US citizenship, you'll need a separate immigrant visa path (marriage, employer sponsorship, or EB-5).</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Choosing Grenada Without US Plans</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">If you don't plan to pursue US E-2, Dominica is $50K cheaper with similar travel benefits (145 vs 146 countries). Grenada's premium only makes sense if E-2 option has value for you. Don't pay extra for a treaty you won't use.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Inadequate Source of Funds Documentation</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Like all CBI programs, Grenada requires clear documentation of investment funds' origin. Bank statements alone aren't enough—need business records, tax returns, contracts. Prepare comprehensive evidence to avoid delays or rejection.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

